   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-04-13_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Harley-Street-31_ENK">Harley S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.</placeName>
                  <date when="1819-04-13">Tuesday 13 <hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1819</date>
               </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>
               <del>The</del>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is going on as well as<lb/>
               possible - she is in my opinion &amp; in<lb/>
               the opinion of all who see her better now<lb/>
               than she was before her illness - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollP1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <choice>
                     <orig>Hol<lb/>
               land</orig>
                     <reg>Holland</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName> never ceases to repeat that we<lb/>
               must not remit care &amp; that she must<lb/>
               be taken from all excitement.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               We go to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BailJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Baillies</persName> to day to dinner<lb/>
               - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH4">Honora</persName>
               <add>
                  <hi rend="superscript">2</hi>
               </add> &amp; <add>
                  <hi rend="superscript">3</hi>
               </add> I &amp; Miss's Carr have been<lb/>
               paying our T F L visits - all finished<lb/>
               I have stopped her for 1/2 an hour.<lb/>
               We breakfasted at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MarcJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Marcets</persName> - <unclear>S<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</unclear>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SebrJ1">J. Seebright</persName> &amp; daughter came in - He gave<lb/>
               me a frank &amp; I must tho I have not<lb/>
               2 minutes send you this bulletin of<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName>.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>On thursday morning we breakfast at<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyds</persName> then come here at 12 - And<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> pronounces her farewell &amp;<lb/> 
               gives her parting advice to <persName cert="high" ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">J.L.</persName> I pity<lb/>
               him from my soul. He has won my<lb/>
               esteem &amp; regard - I wish him all<lb/>
               good - except <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I have requested for the sake of her<lb/>
               health &amp; to save them both from <choice>
                  <orig>unne<lb/>
                     <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-04-13_page02.jpg"/>
                  cessary</orig>
                  <reg/>
               </choice> pain that there should be but<lb/>
               this one decisive meeting - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName>
               <lb/>
               wished this &amp; <persName cert="high" ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">J L</persName> submits - I have<lb/>
               just announced it to him &amp; I never<lb/>
               saw a man suffer more.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               From this house we shall on Thursday<lb/>
               drive directly to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Deep-Dene-Dorking_ENK">Deep Dene</placeName> - where<lb/>
               we can stay only till the 19<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. when<lb/>
               he is obliged to return to Town on<lb/>
               some law business - We shall then<lb/>
               I believe go to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E W's</persName> - we shall<lb/>
               not keep our engagement to <del>Lady</del>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaddX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Taddy</persName> for the 22 &amp; 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. - I thought<lb/>
               it best to quit <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> at once both<lb/>
               for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Fannys</orig>
                     <reg>Fanny's</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName> sake &amp; from delicacy to<lb/>
               <persName cert="high" ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">L W's</persName> feelings who should be spared<lb/>
               surely as much as possible<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I have written to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#TaddX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Taddy</persName> &amp;<lb/>
               &amp; I have refused all other invitations<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH4">Honora</persName> well - no pen can describe<lb/>
               the kindness of the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrX4">Carrs</persName> to us -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <choice>
                  <orig>Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>Your</reg>
               </choice> ever <choice>
                  <orig>affec<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg>affectionate</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">M E</persName>
               <lb/>
               I will write again the moment we get to<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-04-13_page03.jpg"/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Deep-Dene-Dorking_ENK">Deep Dene</placeName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF2">Little Francis</persName> wins all hearts &amp;
               will keep them<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi>
               </persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrF1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Carr</persName> ask me if they might<lb/>
               invite him to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Frognal-Hampstead_ENK">Frognal</placeName> sometimes<lb/>
               on Saturday &amp; Sunday<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I answered that I was sure you<lb/>
               w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> like he should be in such a family
               &amp; that you w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. feel obliged.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I have told <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis B</persName> this &amp; <del>shall</del>
               <lb/>
               he is to be applied to when they want<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF2">little F</persName> - Luckily he has a school<lb/>
               fellow young <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ColeX1">Colebrook</persName> whose rich<lb/>
               father will bring him down<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-04-13_page04.jpg"/>
               <hi rend="underline">Private</hi>
               <lb/>
               <unclear>De</unclear>arest mother as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is writing<lb/>
               &amp; pouring out her heart to you<lb/>
               I need only say that as far as<lb/>
               I can judge her mind has been<lb/>
               much more at ease since the<lb/>
               decision was spoken &amp; the<lb/>
               parting over - she is sorry for him<lb/>
               &amp; she would not be my dear<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> &amp; your dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName>
               <lb/>
               if she were not -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I <hi rend="underline">don't</hi> think she has ever<lb/>
               repented for one moment<lb/>
               nor have I for her - <del>But</del> I think<lb/>
               her father would be proud of<lb/>
               her. for I am clear that her<lb/>
               reason has conquered &amp; decided<lb/>
               against first partiality &amp; linger<lb/>
               ing love. - No more interviews<lb/>
               <unclear>I</unclear> say - He shall never know<lb/>
               when we are at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E W's</persName> or<lb/>
               rather I will at once say we<lb/>
               will not tell you purposely<lb/>
               that you sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. not have the<lb/>
               pain of knowing we are near<lb/>
               you &amp; that you cannot see <hi rend="underline">her</hi>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I have written as kindly to him as I possibly could &amp;<lb/>
               have asked him to take <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF2">little<lb/>
               Francis</persName> to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Hampstead_ENK">Hampstead</placeName> - Surely<lb/>
               his generous conduct deserved<lb/>
               this - He said almost in his<lb/>
               parting words to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">F</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               " I hope I shall still be permitted<lb/>
               " to be kind to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF2">little Francis</persName> for his<lb/>
               " own &amp; his dear mothers sake "<lb/>
               quite touching!<lb/>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
